levels.victoryText: Correct! The carrying capacity (K) controls the maximum number of cells in the total population.

levels.hintText: You can eliminate growth by setting the starting cell number to zero, the growth rate to zero, the carrying capacity to zero, or any combination.
levels.victoryText: Zero growth! Nonzero values for C, r and K are all required for growth. Otherwise the growth curve is a flat line.

levels.hintText: Maximize growth by increasing all of the terms.
levels.victoryText: Maximum growth! High values for K increase the maximum number of cells. High values r makes the population growth increase sharply, and pushes the growth rate to high maximum values.

levels.hintText: Decreasing the starting number of cells will delay the phase of maximum growth.
levels.victoryText: Time Shift! When you begin with few cells, the period of detectable growth is delayed. The cells are still growing, but their numbers are initially too small to be seen on this graph.

levels.hintText: Maximize early growth by starting with more cells. The growth curve will be flat when C = K.
levels.victoryText: Nice curve! A large initial population of cells can reach the carrying capacity quickly, then the growth rate drops to zero.

levels.hintText: Combine what you have learned about delaying the spike in cell growth and setting the maximum number of cells.
levels.victoryText: Yes! Prepare for the ultimate microbiology challenge!

levels.hintText: Use everything you have learned. Be the curve.
levels.victoryText: Excellent! You are now an expert in logistic growth. Use your power only for good.
